<Review>My girlfriend and I stopped by here today since we were in the Burbank area enjoying the nice sunny weather after the rain. She loves Coffee Bean and its so hard to find now near our place due to covid and the mall limitation. But the location in Burbank is always the saver for her. When we got to the place, we were able to just walk up to the counter and put in her order. She loves their Mocha Latte, we actually had our first date at a Coffee Bean but the one in Northridge. It didn't take long for her drink to be ready since there was no other orders pending. Finding parking here would probably be the most difficult part. Due to covid, more spots are available than before but we usually park at the police station down the street since it's easier to get out and is not compact. It also gives you the opportunity to get some steps in and explore Burbank. The customer service we received was also spectacular.</Review><Pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipM1R-x5LORUiLIboclNcJQdq8WPN6lOaZiC-wLK=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMnbi34cMZ5bVJel4PDEe0H3pjp8p15itkV15uc=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMlD69vRxoe0xyANiG567ijY-SY9DeArB3Bh3fN=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipOZ4QsuZp1r-p1MwxZcCvr58NHhTkhsL3G-eYCp=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNDOHx7PWQX-GeiS4jX54_lq3akHG6d-qj5JNhv=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPqDia-7zMsNSq5nv9tbl9oouK5LBWG7ocF1s8j=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipO8SOUu7e_2xetfgLbye7dlAtMK2eUWAQe_sI9W=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMZ7iraYNUn_o3ga_GY5xoAAJvLPK4LI800kJUe=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMxOA64AKNQN3ljVCFhhDzvzYlZh3NlAXZH25Gx=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /Pictures>< Date>

< Text>
It was packed on a Saturday afternoon. Ordered the iced mocha. It was the best iced mocha I have ever had. Soooo much better than Starbucks. They use real small pieces of chocolate and mix it with the coffee. None of the syrup stuff. Delicious! I can't wait to come back and have another cup of iced mocha.</Text>

Ordered two boxes of Java-to-go for meeting, one light roast and one dark roast. I think it's Mexican Organic and Bright future (perfect for our meeting!! Haha). Called ahead and they are ready when arrive (called before 7 for a pick up at 9:30). The barista helps me carry them to my car.

I would definitely look for these two beans (yes it's that good!). :)</text>

<Rate>5< /Rate>< Text>
Had the El Ranchero burrito with steak. I little heavy on beans/sour cream/salsa that made it a little messy, but overall very good. With a drink it was under $10 so it's a pretty good deal too.

Bumping this to 5 stars. The fresh burrito without sour cream was even better somehow. Great homemade taste and friendly service. My only complaint is charging for soda refills when dining in and no chips/salsa bar but I'm sure that's what keeps the prices so low. Definitely worth trying.</Text>

Delicious, authentic Mexican food for a reasonable price.  Everyone was very friendly behind the counter.  The gentleman who took my order offered many other items that weren't on the menu.  I ordered Chile Verde, which is not on the menu, and it was great.  The place itself is small with only a few tables to sit at, but I'd highly recommend it for take-out. <time>1470791217560< /time><rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Friendly dude at front, took our order and brought us our food. No misunderstanding in the order (one does not like onions). Nice typical Mexican ambience nothing too American. No beer girl cardboards which is a plus and had some TVs. Ordered 2 El Ranchero burritos and they were bomb. Even came with guacamole and sour cream inside. Came with chips and side of salsa (customer choice on type I believe). Chips are great and Verde salsa was amazing. Made a great first impression. Will be back for tacos next time.< /Review>

< Rate>

< text>
A Co-worker and I decided to give this place a try on our lunch break, I ordered a Ranchero Burrito with no meat- the lady at the register asked if I wanted no beans? Not sure where she got that, I corrected her and assumed she got my order in the way I explained it.
About 30 minutes had gone by and we still hadn't gotten our food, though other people who had come in long after had. I had to approach the counter and ask if they had forgotten about us- they had. The lady behind the counter didn't seem to care and didn't offer an apology or even some chips for us to munch on while we waited for more than 45 minutes now.
When my burrito finally came, it was just rice- nothing else?! Not what I had ordered AT ALL, plus the TO GO item I had ordered was wrong as well. My friends burrito was missing guac and cheese, so her order was wrong too.
I ended up getting back to work late because it took so long and spent the rest of the afternoon hungry because I only took a few bites of the "rice" burrito I was charged $10.00 for.</text>

< Review>
My wife found this on some list as the Dive Bar wth the best view in the US, so naturally we had to grab a drink here while in Mendocino.  Definitely lives up to that reputation, great view facing south over the bluffs.  Friendly staff with fairly stiff drinks.  Pretty cool local vibe here, definitely not many tourists like us ventured in.  They have an awesome miniature model of the bar that is stunningly accurate.  Lots of great historical photos on the walls. Definitely the best place in town to grab a drink.<//Review>

< Review>
This is a small unique bar with fun decor by the sea in Mendocino. It's a hangout spot for the locals. For your entertainment they have darts in the back room, an old fashioned jukebox, and large screen TV playing sports channels. The beer selection is decent and the staff is friendly.</Review>

They answered everyone of my concerns and did multiple test for my symptoms. Referred me out to an RA that no other doctor would do. They listened to me. I couldn't be happier. Well we will see how long that last since now my doctor is no longer with GVH and I will be seeing a P.A. It's a guy and I can't stand male doctors. UGH!

< review>
I have been going to this car wash location for many years, and this morning I thought I would take my truck to get washed rather than me doing it myself. When I arrived at the car wash the salesman convinced me to get my truck hand waxed with a car wash that included the inside and outside. Well to my disgust, the work was completed faster than normal which made me question the service rendered. To my surprise the car was washed very superficially with road grime still on the hood, grill, head lights and all over the truck. Inside the truck it was even worse, it was left with dust on most surfaces and the floor mats where left dirty. When they delivered the truck to me I started to point out the areas they had missed and the workers and their supervisor stated that they had done what the service required. I had them call over the salesman and they proceeded to clean a little more (still left sub-par). There was no apology for the sub-par work, in fact I got the feeling they had no regrets how they had treated me.  Also to my regret, I noticed some of the workers bad mouthing me in Spanish. To say the least, I am very disappointed with the service I was rendered.

I will not be using this place to clean my truck or cars any longer!</review>

<rating>4<//rating><text>The establishment itself is well maintained and clean, but it is located in a ungentrified part of LA. It reminded me of Mexico, where there are a lot of street vendors selling drinks and food on about every street corner.  I'm not usually in this part of town so I can't speak about how it really is on the day to day. I came with my boyfriend to get their famous pastrami sandwich and that was well worth the trip. Only thing to look out for is that the Langer's parking lot is for employees only. We came when they opened so no one was in the booth in the parking lot. There is metered parking on the street which is free on Sundays.</text>< pics>

<name>Rajeev Dav√©<//name><rate>5<//rate>< time>

< review>
Tl;dr : Go early (or order for curbside) & go hungry.

I can only compare this LA institution to others such as Katz' NYC and Harold's in New Jersey... Langer's punches its weight.
Sandwiches are smaller than the monsters served at the east coast meccas (but still generous). Pickles and mustard are milder.
Crowds are better-managed and the rye bread is surprisingly superior.
We had the #19 (pastrami with slaw and Russian dressing on rye) and shared some fries. No one left hungry.< /review>

< review>
This was my first time coming to Langers. I came early with a friend to miss the the lines that form outside, but even when we left there was still not a line on the Friday we ate there.  I got a club sandwich that came with turkey and tongue and beef, but I substituted bacon for the beef. It was excellent.  So big I had to take half of it home.  Definitely not inexpensive - $22 for sandwich. But I don't think there is anywhere else in Los Angeles that you can get a club sandwich with tongue! üòÄ My friend and I split an order of fries, which were very good. She had a pastrami sandwich with a cheese called nippy.  She was very happy with her sandwich. I will definitely try to make it across town again to have lunch there.</review>

The best pastrami, great rye bread. What else can one day this is a Los Angeles classic!</Text>

<userid>111493143260079947904< /userid><Name>Hiep Nguyen< /Name><Date>1527287291236< /Date><Rating>5</Rating>< Review>
The pastrami is flavourful and rye bread is nice as well. The crust is crunchy, giving the sandwich a nice texture. The inside is soft, warm, and packed with goodies. It is not filled up like Katz (if that's what you are looking to compare) but I did not feel the lack of meatiness.

I got number 19 and coselaw was good, not sure if I would get it cheese again. The Russian dressing made it different and I got what was looking for (slightly sweet and rich sauce vs. just mustard).

Overall I would recommend it, the size is good to share. I will definitely be back for their other dishes.

PS. I tried their chopped liver. The flavor was intense and tasted too rich for me (very heavy seasoning of garlic and onions). You can definitely taste the liver though, but other spicing overwhelmed it.<//Review>

Two words....corned beef and pastrami.  Here is one of LA few remaining institutions that should be on your bucket list.  If you like either of the two then this establishment is 5 stars for any sandwich made with any one of those meats. They still do it the old way with hand cut meats and real rye bread.  The only reason why it's 4 stars is due to the NY pricing often which this establishment is compared to, but even with the high cost of a sandwich I still go back once a month.  Pro tip....call in your order for curbside pickup.<//Text>

< review>
Langer's Deli is a culinary icon of Los Angeles, and they serve one of the best hot pastrami sandwiches I've ever had. The #19 comes with hand-cut thick slices of pastrami, a perfect ratio of cooling coleslaw, Russian dressing and Swiss cheese, all sandwiched between rye bread. It's a perfect balance of flavors, textures, and temperatures in your mouth all at the same time. Must-eat for any food lover in or visiting LA.< /review>

Parking is a bit hard around this area so I lyfted over with a couple friends and line goes by quickly, very organized and structured with their seating system. <review>First time here, life long LA resident. I hate when a place gets hyped up on how good it is just because it's been there since the beginning of time. That being said, I can tell you this place did not let me down!  This has been by far the best pastrami I've had so far and I can't even remember what would be second to this.  It's tender, flavorful and the sweet tang from the Russian Dressing is fantastic.  I came in at 9am on a Tuesday, so it wasn't jam packed like it usually is so I got seated right away. Our server, Sheila, was such a sweet lady and made my daughter smile. Their hours are 8-4pm, so unless you work in the area, you'll have to take the day off to go here.... which is very worth the time.</review><pics>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMQb7YDcRaVw4Zq2RqfeqRMr0WWupkfifQg32RK=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMDtY6qhWBa6wB46pUYBIUUSCzIyTY-_6KFXDDF=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNZNhTjYg0zHf6rUvvAuLYrGMKeGddI3U1EV8p_=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]< /pics>< response>

< text>
OMG I never knew pastrami could taste this good! LoL. I love the old feel of this place. We ordered the #19 I think (it's one of their more popular sandwiches) It comes with pastrami, coleslaw, cheese, and , Russian dressing and we also ordered the pastrami fries. The pastrami is literally melt on your mouth good and the fries were great as well the only thing was that I felt like the chili was the brick chili and I dont really like that. Definately go on a cheat day! There is metered parking out front but it's best to just park in their lot and it's literally like a block down and a short walk back.</text>

< user>
116384712996537560303< /user>
<user_name>Jimmy Kimmel</user_name>< time>
1558208628051</time>
< rating>
5<//rating>
< Review>
My NYC friend was in town again recently and could have knocked me over with a feather when he suggested going to Langer's: an LA institution!!
Why knock me over? because this is a dyed in the wool New Yorker who would usually make the ugly face when i suggested going to an LA deli. This dude was raised on Katz's and the Carnegie Deli food and whose parents spoon fed him rice pudding at those venerable joints.
In any event after i picked myself up off the floor we made the short trek to Alvarado very early one morning recently and ordered 2 of the famous number 19: Pastrami on Rye with Swiss and Slaw, side of Potato salad.
I have been going to Langer's for what seems like 100 years but in reality since the 1970's though i haven't been for about 10 years.
This is the type of place in which there are least a couple of veteran employees that will recognize you and one who asked me about my Pops who kicked the proverbial bucket 20 years ago!
I remember going with Pops on Saturday morning to eat fried eggs and toast and once in a while he would let me drink coffee. (this was a more innocent time when teens did not drink coffee for fear of "stunting" their growth!)
We stared, mouths agape when the 19's arrived at our counter space: this was a beautiful thing to behold. And ultimately a beautiful thing to eat:
super fresh, pillowy rye bread with a slightly crispy edge. Note: this is real old style rye made with a good percentage of rye flour and seeds.
The Pastrami here is supremely tender, slightly pickley, peppery, smoky with the appropriate amount of fat that tasted so fresh that i bet it had just come out of the smoker being that it was very early in the AM.
The Slaw added crunch and a piquant vinegar astringency to the sammy. The Swiss and their famous Russian dressing were along for the ride to smooth out the overall taste. There are a lot of things pulling at your taste buds screaming: Eat Me! Love Me! But it all comes together at the conclusion of every bite.
The Langer people are quick, super efficient and sassy and most have been here for many years. These are professional people who take their jobs seriously. And it shows.< /Review>

The chopped liver and herring in cream sauce was thrown in the garbage. I paid $43 today for crappie food and a bad attitude. They get two stars because their pastrami is still one of the best. Along with a pastrami sandwich I took home half pints of chopped liver, herring in cream sauce, cole slaw and a loaf of rye. The chopped liver has a mealy consistency, an odd flavor and probably full of filler. The herring is in a thin milky sauce, lacking the traditional thicker cream sauce and the fish is too fishy tasting. Its off on taste and texture. The deli man seemed  Inconvenienced by my order. My bad review won't make a dent in this businesses traffic flow, but as a lifelong deli consumer I hate to see one of the last great delis serve lousy food.< /review>

Langers has been on my restaurant hit list for a  while. I had the opportunity to savor, perhaps  the best  French Dip pastramy and roast beef sandwiches in town. My family and I arrived on Sunday, an hour before closing. There was no waiting. my wife and daughter, being fans of cafe counters, quickly took our spot front center of the kitchen. Our waiter was friendly and very patient with us. Our dishes were served on a timely manner and  hot. We also had the opportunity to meet the owner who was very friendly and even gave my daughter free fries, because he said I was being greedy with my chili cheese fries üòÅ, I'll admitted, just a little. Then again, who wouldn't, they're so good! Overall, it was great experience that's defenitely worth repeating. Update, we have returned twice since my review, the hot pastrami sandwhich, accompany with sauerkraut on rye, is a must.</text>

<date>1595957779119< /date><GmapID>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501</GmapID>< Review>
The World's best Pastrami sandwich, hands down! Over 10 years ago I had this sandwich in my early 20's, way back when my food palette and appreciation for good quality food was non existent. I remember thinking that this pastrami was different from Tam's Pastrami, or the local burger joints Pastrami, mind you that was the only food I'd ever really known. Unfortunately at that time I thought "man Langers isn't much, it was ok but it wasn't all that". Oh if I could go back in time and slap myself for thinking that, oh what blasphemy lol.

Well im happy to say that these days im in a much better place with a completely different understanding, palette, appreciation, and hunger for food. Langers Pastrami is head and shoulders above the rest, this sandwich is often imitated but never duplicated. The Pastrami is cooked to a juicy tender perfection. The rye bread is the perfect complement to absorb and hold all the juicyness of that delicious pastrami. Layered in perfect harmony with their dressing and coleslaw, along with a crisp pickle on the side, the famous #19 delivers on every level to deliver a satisfaction unlike any other.<//Review>

<user>108522379501537435607</user><Date>1577718778581</Date><gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501</gmap_id><username>hutasoit jaya</username></record>

<gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501</gmap_id><Name>David Bradshaw</Name><Response>None<//Response><rating>5</rating>< text>
Always amazing. Consistently some of the best pastrami I've ever had. Incredibly juicy and flavorful. They use less meat in the sandwiches than they used to, but the price hasn't changed for many years. This is in some ways a good thing; inflation aside, the sandwiches 20 years ago were larger than anyone other than the biggest eaters could handle in one sitting. Now they're manageable by someone like me who has a big appetite. The delicious rye bread is a big part of the equation, made in huge long loaves by a process I can't fathom. I recently discovered a pastrami scramble which is killer. Free parking across the street. I was amazed that there was no waiting on a Saturday late morning- prime brunch time.<//text>

<Resp>None</Resp><Rating>4<//Rating><review>A belated lunch review on weekdays.
Restaurant is almost half full, quite busy during lunch hour.
Parked across the street in their destinated parking lot, don't forget to get validation after your meal for free parking.

Get seated right away. Old style seating booth type of sofas, not too comfy and there's always someone needed to use bathroom among your group, in and out, making you get up and down from your seat. Some tables are very close to each other, that's a little too close with your neighbor lunch mate.

Waiter is somewhat patience to explain different types of sandwiches and meats and give you recommendations. Tried out a few new stuff because some of us are newbies to Langer's.

Food is great but you have to know what to order. Someone order turkey burger at our table and that's not the place for turkey burger, right?!

** Con - no split check. All in one check and you have to figure how you want to pay at the register in the front. Bathroom is tight, use it at the end.<//review>< gmapID>

< Text>
Until I retired 13 years ago, working downtown LA,  I would eat at Langers several times a year and ALWAYS loved it...their rye bread is to die for as is the pastrami and sweet/sour cabbage soup. Retiring and living in Riverside I rarely get to go there anymore and miss it very much. So, for my birthday my daughter sent me a Langer's pastrami package complete with rye bread, cole slaw and THE BEST PASTRAMI IN THE WORLD..and I am from NYC and know my pastrami..the meat was soooo flavorful and tasty AND lean..really cannot possibly get any better....My wife says the same, also an ex NYer... I sure miss not being able to eat there as I used to. OMG THEY ARE THE GREATEST!< /Text>

< Text>
it's in a bit of a rough area and while it does have some parking that parking gets filled up and so you have to find street parking. I had seen which number 19 which is their best seller. It's a bit pricey it's a good portion but it has no side. The bread is some of the best I've ever had. The pastrami is not the best I've ever had or the second-best it's very good but it comes in so highly rated you set very high expectations. staff are very friendly and I was served very quickly. Eating at the countertop saves you wait time. not quite worth the hassle getting there but it is a good one time experience.<//Text>

<review>I have been wanting to come here for awhile now. With my work schedule, it just doesn't work out and Saturdays get too crazy. When I took a day off of work on a random Monday, I figured this was going to be the only time I can try it. I came there around 12:30/1PM on a Monday afternoon. There was no wait, hallelujah!

The atmosphere and decor really surprised me when I walked in-- in a good way! It was huge inside and the refreshing to see part of the place still had a deli and bakery with an old school bar seating area. The staff greeted us with a friendly and welcoming attitude.

Per our waiter's recommendation, we went with the #19 and the #88 and some fries. Our waiter was extremely welcoming and came to check in on us a couple times to refill water and ice tea. The corned beef Reuben was great. It was warm and soft, but since it's grilled, very crunchy on the outside. The sauerkraut was a good balance to the cheese and saltiness of the beef. You take a bite of the pickle and it's a bit sour-- so you wash it down with some fries. However, as soon as I took my first bite of the #19, I was in love. I knew that if I ever came here again, it would be for the #19. You have to acidity, creaminess, and crunch of the slaw to balance with the pickle, and the cheese, pastrami, and the soft bread. I was never a fan of rye bread, or anything multigrain because I like my bread to have a soft texture, but I did not mind this rye bread!

Definitely worth the hype if you are ever to wait the lines or take a random day off to come here!!</review><userid>103158147270027752547<//userid><Date>1569604805234</Date>< Resp>

< Review>
This is probably the best pastrami sandwich I've ever eaten EVER! I thought in New York the one deli was the spot but NOPE, handsdown! When you look at the menu, the price seems steep but it's totally worth it! You can share one sandwich no problem as well be sure to try the pastrami chilli cheese fries and the matzo ball soup!! The meat is succulent and the crispy cold coleslaw has the perfect texture and not too sloppy! But the pickle was the grand finale for me!!! Will be back again!!! Free parking validation as well!!!!< /Review>

< review>
We have visited Langer's for many times so I think this is the right time to leave this restaurant a review.

If you want a place with a wide variety of sandwiches, then this is the place you have to visit. They have incredible and original sandwiches. I am a huge fan of their pastrami sandwiches. They have the perfect bread for a sandwich. Well flavored and really creative sandwiches. They also have a wide variety of dressings. Their dressings are what bring a fun twist to their sandwiches. Although a bit pricey but I think it is just fair enough. For me, they have the best pastrami in Los Angeles area. If you are in the area and you want a good and deli sandwich, you should give them a try. I am sure they won't let you down.

By the way, this place has a lot of customers so expect it to be a little crowded.<//review>

<name>Alexandria Damiano<//name><date>1500334736755<//date>< rating>
4<//rating>
< Review>
I've been a Canter's girl all my 27 years, and still love it. But, when my boyfriend finally introduced me to Langer's Pastrami-etc? Oh my.

PERFECT meat to fat ratio, awesome pickles, lovely dressings.

The ONLY reason for lacking that starry-eyed 5th star every restaurant seeks, slightly steep "normal" prices aside, is the hours. You guys could do business 24-hours, easily, and still bank more than a profit. And get to see the more "interesting" late night LA people as icing on the cake. (Or mustard on the pastrami, more appropriately. :) )</Review>

110126637037593272681<//user>
<pics>None<//pics><Rating>5< /Rating><review>Langer's really is all that!

Cons: Not the best of neighborhoods. Parking is one block up on the opposite side of 7th Street (free with validation). Frequently there is rope line outside to get in. Not open for dinner. Seating and aisles are a bit snug. The prices are a bit high.

Pros: The quality of the food and service more than surpasses the cons. We're talking about one of the finest Jewish deli & diners in the country. First rate ingredients & preparation. Many are made in house. The staff is friendly, courteous, and professional.

Pro tips: Drop your fellow guests at the door side passenger unloading/loading zone, then go park up the block at the Langer's parking lot on the opposite side of 7th Street. Get a parking lot ticket, they validate at the cashier. Ask what the flavor is of the in-house soda, it changes. Leave a worthy tip. Leave with your leftovers, they will hold up.<//review></record></dataset><record>

<user>102194127806890955286<//user>< Rating>
3< /Rating>
< time>
1485461144347< /time>
<Gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501<//Gmap_id>< review>
Everything is about twice as expensive as it ought to be. There are no extras to offset the overpricing. A bagel with lox and cream cheese and mealy tomatoes didn't include capers or cucumbers. Sure, it came with half a decent homemade pickle and  four pitted black olives from a can on the side but, was it worth $18 before tax? No, of course not. The servers are sweet at times. They can be amazingly slow to get to the table though. You can't get them to settle your bill from the table. You HAVE to go stand in line and deal with the slow, detached service of the cashiers. People are in lines around the corner for this on the weekends?

Do yourself a favor and avoid lines by dropping in during the week.

I have been to Langer's in a pinch, feeling sick, desperate for chicken soup, and glad to have at least something resembling a deli in the area.<//review>

4<//rate>
< Review>
The #19 was amazingly well prepared, balanced, and tasty. Pastrami cuts were thick, juicy, lean (not thin and greasy), and very, very tender. Rye bread has a crispy crust and fluffy light interior. The slaw, dressing, and cheese are perfectly proportioned and complement the whole sandwich wonderfully. I've had pastrami in New York and would take Langer's over NY any day. Nice staff (sometimes rushed) and cool atmosphere (feels like a Mafia diner). A bit pricey but its worth it, at least once.< /Review>

<text>This is the best pastrami sandwich I've ever had. Hands down, best pastrami ever.

It's not in the best neighborhood, but it's SO GOOD. The deli is open at finicky hours, and the nearby swap meets attract an unsavory crowd of folks, but this little gem of a deli is totally worth the trip.

These guys do curbside delivery, but I highly encourage anyone to come in, have a pastrami, and look at the nostalgia of Los Angeles inside the restaurant. There's a story behind this place, and one of those stories begins with the legendary pastrami sandwich. The other food? It's just as good. Don't forget dessert.<//text>< UserId.>

5<//rating>
< Review>
Well, this place is an icon! It was well worth the drive to DTLA for it, too. All I have to say is pastrami pastrami pastrami!!! They are famous for their pastrami sandwiches and rightfully so. There is parking across the street in a monitored lot which makes things easier. Langer's rests on the middle of downtown across the street from MacArthur Park. Not the safest area in Los Angeles, but the walk from the parking lot to the restaurant should be fine. Langer's usually sports a line out the door. That's what kind of place this is. At the time of day we went, it was still packed and no line to get in. We sat down and each ordered a pastrami sandwich and an order of pastrami chili fries. Needless to say, half of it came home with us. I find myself craving this sandwich. Must try if you have guests from out of town. A lot to see down there and the patrons are the Untied Colors of Benetton. Very diverse.<//Review>

< rating>
5<//rating>
<text>Is Nirvana just a theological state of being, or is it something you can taste?  Langer's Deli has the answer to this riddle in sandwich form.

Don't get me wrong; I still love Johnny's Pastrami in Culver City and Canter's Deli in Fairfax District, but Langer's has them beat if for only one reason: Langer's pastrami is not too lean; Johnny's and Canters' is.  Trimming all the fat from pastrami kills the flavor, so if you care more about your cholesterol intake than you do about flavor (in other words, you're one of those damn metrosexuals that always make me want to punch something, preferably them and ruin their ultra-styled hair and makeup), go eat a tofu burger and pretend you like it, bozo.

If I have one complaint about Langer's, it's the price.  I wouldn't pay $14 for one sandwich (a satisfying sandwich, but hardly enormous) unless it was one hell of a sandwich.  And as this was my first time eating at Langer's--and I can't WAIT to go again--this qualifies as such.  Sure, Johnny's is a better deal at eight or nine bucks (and they ARE huge), but as much as I like them, they just can't compare.  And Canter's sandwiches may contain more meat and cost about the same as Langer's, but when the meat is that lean, it simply lacks flavor, so I'll stick to the roast beef when I go to Canter's.

So if you're not a stinking metrosexual or dim-witted member of PETA and are able to exercise a modicum of moderation (meaning try not to have more than five pastrami sandwiches a week), you will adore Langer's sandwiches as much as I do.  Just be sure to ask them to be sure NOT to put coleslaw on your sandwich, because sometimes they just can't help themselves.< /text><time>1504468665657< /time>< Name>
Tom Wagner<//Name>

0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501</GmapID>

<rating>4< /rating>< Review>
Incredible Rye bread and arguably the best Pastrami in the country, definitely in LA. I was however disappointed at the portions (I would prefer more Pastrami and overall bigger sandwiches) and also in the prices. Who wants to pay more than $15 for a Pastrami Sandwich with russian dressing and coleslaw? Its a joke really but they do it because they can, they know they have a great product and people line up all day for it.
Also, the location blows.
Great review because I always base reviews off food, its one of the best corned beef sandwiches anywhere, period. Portion size and experience of eating the sandwich brings it down to 4 stars.< /Review>

The food sucked though. We got pastrami sandwiches and latkes. No sauerkraut, only cole slaw, which I know is done sometimes but still disappointing, and otherwise all of the food was REALLY under par. < text>
Best Deli in LA! best known for their #19.  Slow cooked pastrami is hand cut to order, with tangy cole slaw on top. The twice baked rye is made on the premises. Light crispy crust with soft rye center. Also old school Briney and sour pickles. These are tye type that they had in old pickle barrels back in the day.If you live in LA , make the schlep.</text>

< text>
I would rate this place 6 stars if I could.  It is pricey but definately something you should try at least once in your life.  Get the world famous #19 pastrami with coleslaw, swiss, and Russian dressing.  The pastrami chili cheese fries were also really good. Pro tip: They have their own parking with validation. "Langer‚Äôs maintains its own, monitored parking lot at the northeast corner of 7th Street and Westlake, one block east of our restaurant location. Parking is validated for 90 minutes; please get the ticket from the attendant and have it stamped by the cashier when you leave."</text>

Yes, the area is a bit seedy, and you'd better keep your hand on your wallet as you walk there, but there is no better pastrami sandwich in the country.  I personally like the sandwich with the cole slaw and dressing, but my family mostly gets the plain sandwich with a slice of cheese. <user_id>107063077542687998922<//user_id><name>Jobie Low< /name>< Time>
1535147979651</Time>
< Rate>
5<//Rate>
<review>Came here by chance, looking for a place for lunch. Remembered Langer's from "I'll Have What Phil's Having" with Norman Lear and Paul Reiser to have a deli sandwich. Had the #19-pastrami, Swiss, coleslaw, but on toasted sourdough as per significant other (preferred the rye but eh, no biggie). Sandwich is pretty perfect, balancing the hot pastrami (can really taste the seasonings of the meat) with the crunch of a well-prepared coleslaw that complements the flavors of the Swiss and sourdough (still think rye woulda been better but now I'm being whiney...). Don't forget to order fries-crinkle cut crunchy outside with a soft inside, not over-salted, cut just the right size, and a small order feeds two easily.
The service was very, very cordial even after a busy lunch service (we were in a line of 15 outside the door at about 1:15 but the line moves). Our waiter was helpful with suggestions, even dessert. Got the apples pie with brandy sauce and a slice of chocolate cake. The pie came out piping hot, would have liked more apples but still pretty tasty. The chocolate cake was heavenly-three layers of moist not-too-sweet chocolate cake, whipped cream, and a dusting of chocolate. Hey, this isn't a fancy-pants place so don't expect fancy-pants food, but Langer's has been around longer than I have and they still pack'em in for lunch well after lunchtime.
The area isn't the best but the food makes up for any paranoia you may have.
Langer's has got the Jewish deli down!</review><Pics>None</Pics>< Resp>
None</Resp>

<date>1487958273519</date><Rating>5<//Rating>< Text>
Historic restaurant, been here since the 50's. Kosher food and probably the best pastrami sandwich in town.  If your not use to urban Los Angeles you might find the area a bit sketchy but I worked in this area for years and never had a safety issue.  Parking is difficult but they offer parking a block away on the corner of 7th and Westlake.< /Text>

< user>
105432250794694053311</user>
<Pictures>None</Pictures>< review>
Delicious!  About $16 per pastrami sandwich, fries not included.
The parking in the surrounding area is terrible but there's a small lot with a Langer's sign, you can park there, walk west one short block to the restaurant and get your ticket validated at Langer's when you pay the check at the cashier. I believe they said up to 90 minutes free with validation. About a 15 minute wait, during lunch hour. I had the pastrami on rye w/swiss,  my friend had the classic pastrami on rye but it comes with coleslaw. It looked really good too definitely not the average slaw. He paid $40 for sandwiches and my lemonade. Other half was lunch the next day.<//review>

My son had raved about Langers for years and said they had the best pastrami sandwich in LA. So I went, my mouth watering with anticipation. I was soooo disappointed! I had the PASTRAMI and SWISS CHEESE Russian Style Dressing, and it was, at best, meh. It was also a ripoff of the Nate n' Al sandwich at Nate n' Al's which is a far better deli, has a much better atmosphere, and you don't have to risk your life going there. I wish I could be more positive, but, meh.< /Text>

<text>Langer's Deli has mouthwateringly delicious pastrami, the best in L.A. without a doubt! Their potato salad is amazing as well and I have yet to taste the plethora of other amazing eats they have at this grand landmark. Norm, owner and son of Al Langer, the originator of Langer's Deli is a great and friendly guy and everyone else is great as well which contributes to and completes the wonderful atmosphere that this place has. HIGHLY RECOMMENDED! If you live in L.A. and haven't had Langer's yet then what's your excuse?? Get over here to this awesome landmark of Los Angeles and try the pastrami sandwiches they offer. Spoke with Jeanette Langer, Norm's wife after my meal and she's very sweet, friendly and kind like her husband and everyone else at Langer's Deli. <name>Diana Lin<//name><Text>So this is stop #3 of my self-inflicted L.A. pastrami tour...and I'm proud that I'm still alive.  While other restaurants have been anti-climactic after a multitude of accolades, this deli does not disappoint.

I am proud to say, that I now UNDERSTAND the accolades from The New Yorker, David Sax, Garrett Snyder, and the James Beard Foundation.   I took Snyder's advice & ordered the "plain pastrami sandwich" in true minimalist fashion for take-out for lunch at the office.

The bread was divine: crunchy on the outside & soft upon the 2nd phase of my bite.  The pastrami was complex, marbled, & full of surprises (just how I like it).  My nightmares of ending up in a hospital for high cholesterol...or damned to a bootcamp for the overweight are well worth it ; )< /Text><rating>4</rating><Pictures>None<//Pictures><time>1354692985446<//time><gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501</gmap_id><resp>None< /resp><user>115697281398825437441< /user></record></dataset><record>

<Gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501</Gmap_id>< Resp>
None</Resp>
<text>I never liked pastrami until I had the #19.

Thanks to my brother who stops by here every so often for lunch, he brought me back a half sandwich to try.

Oh my goodness, after one bite I fell in love. Like all other pastramis that are piled with just meat, I like the fact that the #19 has coleslaw with the Russian dressing to cut the saltiness and meaty-ness of the sandwich. I always ask for extra coleslaw and Russian dressing because I just LOVE how creamy and delicious it is.The rye bread is nice and soft.

To complement my sandwich, I always get a side of fries, which are nicely fried and golden.

When you walk-in, you feel a sense on nostalgia, like you just walked into some diner in a Goodfellas movie. The hospitality is also wonderful here.</text>< Rating>
5</Rating>

<user>100256365300259262664< /user><name>John Peters<//name><date>1595278655936<//date><Rating>5</Rating>< text>
Best Pastrami in Los Angeles üòãüòãüòã<//text>
<pictures>None</pictures>< Resp>
None< /Resp>
<gmapID>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501< /gmapID></record></dataset><record>
<Response>None</Response>< Rating>
5<//Rating>
< text>
Every journey has a beginning and an end.  What is now known, bifurcatively, as the Red and Purple Lines, depending on where you want to go, was not so long ago called the Pastrami Express, and now is Metro Rail's trunk line, which initially was  a mere 5  rail stations, in TOTAL length for traveler's embarking from Union Station,and, then, office workers escaping City Hall, who needed to be gently encouraged to utilize the entire new system. One could just imagine the curt brainstorming session in some smoke filled room, where a pearl of  gastronomic wisdom encountering  bureaucratic need quickly coalesced, and in jest, emanated truth, and the truth simply is... Langers.  Talk about justifiable government intervention. The East Coast (read New York City) might have the much venerated Katz's Deli(been there - what do you think the K. stands for!!!), but we Angelenos have... Langers. Almost enough said.  Pastrami on Rye, Deli mustard, a little horseradish, a dill pickle, and some seltzer water, and you're in business.   Maybe some chicken soup with a matzo ball.  An egg cream, possibly?     Langer's is one of those holdouts that has defied demographic change, and with good reason.  If you come from a cultural experience were something like paprika can massively impact the taste buds you'll understand, if not then there are some wonderful dining alternatives just steps away, and available countywide. Langer's is for meat lovers, not condiment lovers. Not that there is anything wrong with their condiments, but I am kvetching here.    Pastrami aficionados/aficionadas take heed, whatever you've tried many believe this is the gold standard for pastrami and to a lesser extent standard Americanized Central European style fare.  Several well off East Coast transplants send their gofers here, I could name names, but would probably be sued for alienation of affection due to open representation of their hidden guilty pleasures.  Go. Sit. Order. Engage in friendly kibitz/conversation.   Enjoy< /text>
< user_name>
Steven Katz<//user_name>

Langer's has been a favorite breakfast place for over three decades. If you want to be impressed by an expeditious, warm, and friendly service, sit at the counter and experience Barbara's service. <Gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501<//Gmap_id>< Text>
Hands down the best pastrami on the planet. I have had Katz's, Stage, Carnegie and Junior's in NY and Langer's is the best. Katz's is really good though too. I am not sure I have ever had anything besides the #44, which is a pastrami reuben. I know reuben purists will probably be critical of it not having swiss, but instead their nippy cheese. It is my favorite sandwich on the planet. I told my wife if I had to choose anything for my last meal it would be this sandwich. The location is not great and from what I have heard isn't the most safe at night, but I have only went there for lunch, which is perfectly safe during the day. Free validated parking too. LOVE LOVE LOVE this place!<//Text>

<Text>Ok...shut up and take my money!

Rye bread and coleslaw had never tasted so good until they met the pastrami at Langer's. Normally I would not get the Rye bread, and I don't like coleslaw. But the juice, greasy, thick slices of pastrami at Langer's just brings the family all together into a unbelievably yummy sandwich. URGH, just thinking about it makes my mouth water.

Sure, it's like $15 bucks for a sandwich, and subway has $5 footlongs all day, and after tax and stuff, its like almost $17 for that famous #19. Here's a little trick to make yourself feel slightly better about spending that dough. It's the BEST IN LA. ITS THE BEST IN LA. I always have to tell myself that. No joke.

Best Pastrami sandwich in LA. Hands down. Hope they never change. Except for maybe their hours of operations. They close super early on weekdays, and closed on Sundays. Every time I'm here, It's always on a Saturday. So if I am ever in DTLA on a weekday looking for lunch, you'll know where I'll be at.< /Text><Gmap_id>0x80c2c79f65c05a3f:0x36ae812febfdc501<//Gmap_id>< Response>

<Time>1530688166968<//Time><Name>kristina flaishans<//Name><response>None<//response>< rate>
5<//rate>
</record></dataset><record>
<user>105922283318214063748< /user><user_name>Stephanie Han< /user_name><date>1421359249447< /date>< rate>
4</rate>
< Text>
Had it not been for some good friends who got me down here I might still be a Langer's virgin, and what a shame that would be! I must confess, I'm not a big pastrami person. I think it's delicious, sure, but I usually don't seek it out. But since this is supposed to be Ground Zero for pastrami in LA, I had to try it. I opted for the #10, so I could get the cole slaw on the side. Took a little while for the sammy to come out, but wow, when it did was it good. The pastrami itself was quite lean, which I guess it always isn't the case, and to tell you the truth I could've used a little more fat in there, but it was still quite delish. What really made the sandwich for me though was their rye bread with the wonderful crunchy crust! And the Russian dressing was a tangy creamy treat as well. It was so good I ended up eating the whole thing, even though just a half would've been quite enough to satisfy. Dan H and I were saying later we should've just split a sandwich between us--oh well! Their cole slaw was quite good as well, fresh, crisp and sweet with just the right amount of mayo. I think I prefer slaw that has cabbage sliced a bit more substantially with more celery seeds, though, so I can't say this was the best slaw I've had. Next time I want to try their tongue sandwich and the chopped liver, as those are usually the items I go for at a Jewish deli.

Getting here and finding parking's no picnic, so prepare yourself. It's a SUPER-busy intersection teeming with more pedestrians than you've ever seen in LA, probably. I thought I was on Avenida Revolucion for a sec (that's Tijuana, folks). Even though their parking lot was full I was able to find free street parking a couple of blocks away, which is probably a good thing, considering how much I pigged out. The decor and ambiance is nothing to write home about, although it's clean and comfortable. The prices are kind of steep too, but those are all small matters considering their awesome food. It was definitely worth it and will have me coming back for more!</Text>
